    Jul 25, 2012 03:15 PM UTC 
    Thanks Doug,

I think we may now be in luck!

I wound up having to do:

[kpcleary@magic ~]$ cat /etc/gridftp.conf
# globus-gridftp-server configuration file

# this is a comment

# option names beginning with '$' will be set as environment variables, e.g.
# $GLOBUS_ERROR_VERBOSE 1
# $GLOBUS_TCP_PORT_RANGE 50000,51000

# port
port 2811
log_level ERROR,WARN,INFO
log_single /var/log/gridftp-auth.log
log_transfer /var/log/gridftp.log
#load_dsi_module posix
hostname 128.205.43.200
control_interface 128.205.43.200
data_interface 128.205.43.200

Despite the RSV probe saying some weird things I am now able to gridftp from multiple hosts.  I will now test lcg-cp.

--
Kevin

-- by Kevin Cleary
    Jul 24, 2012 06:19 PM UTC 
    I think we may have taken a step backwards with the last update.  The server is not responding on port 2811 anymore, so I am not sure what happened there.

There are two channels for gridftp, the control channel (port 2811) and the data channel (in passive mode, now on ephemeral ports 15000-19999).
They should probably both be pointing to the public interface.  Before, the data chnanel was pointing to the private nic.  Now, I am not quite sure exactly what is happening, since it is unavailable, but I am taking a guess that the control channel is not binding to the public interface correctly?  Or perhaps a syntax error is causing problems?  (see below, maybe "data-interface" vs "data_interface" maybe?)  I would check "ps -ef | grep gridftp" to make sure that the process is running, and "netstat -an | grep 2811" to see if it bound to the port.

You may need to play around with the network settings listed in Appendix A on this page:
http://www.globus.org/toolkit/docs/5.2/5.2.2/gridftp/admin/#gridftp-admin-command
I am not exactly sure what is appropriate for your server.  My guess is that you would need something like:
port 2811
log_level ERROR,WARN,INFO
log_single /var/log/gridftp-auth.log
log_transfer /var/log/gridftp.log
hostname magic.cse.buffalo.edu
control_interface magic.cse.buffalo.edu
data_interface magic.cse.buffalo.edu

Though, after writing this that the command-line has "data-interface" and the configuration file has "data_interface" and I said the wrong one in the previous email, so that might be the issue!

Doug Strain
OSG Software

I think this is because the server is not handling passive mode requests to ports 15000-19999 correctly.  Ie. look at the debug output for uberftp client below for an example.  It is attempting to redirect to 192.168.0.1.  Is this behind a NAT device?

I see there is an option to set the data interface in these circumstances for "data-interface <real ip/hostname>".
Try adding this to /etc/gridftp.conf to see if it works.
For more infromation, see this page: http://www.globus.org/toolkit/docs/5.2/5.2.2/gridftp/admin/#gridftp-config-security-firewalls

    Jul 17, 2012 04:01 PM UTC 
    Based on your test results, it looks like this is definitely a network issue, since you can access it from the local network, but not from outside.
However, the firewall settings look fine to me.

Do you have these set in either /etc/sysconfig/globus-gridftp-server or /var/lib/osg/globus-firewall? (Either one is fine)

export GLOBUS_TCP_PORT_RANGE=<begin port>,<end port>
export GLOBUS_TCP_SOURCE_RANGE=<begin port>,<end port>

These should match your firewall settings (ie "15500,19999").

Are there any other firewalls in the network path that could be causing problems?

    Hi Kevin,

In short it is fine to run only a gridftp server if the VOs you support
are OK with it. A gridftp server it is the simpliest version of a SE. some
more avanced functions require a SRM server but sime users are fine
without them.
So you can start with a simple single gridftp server and do something more
complex if you need to scale or someone requires you so.

    May 16, 2012 05:46 PM UTC by Marco Mambelli 
    Hi Scot, Kevin,
I think there may be 2 problems:
1. the CA certificates dir does not have the correct content (at least it has extra files)
2. the probe tries to evaluate the MD5 sum of all certificates in your CA certificates directory. If you have a file corrupted or with wrong permissions in that directory it will fail (report unknown). That should not happen (I don't see why a corrupted certificate should be in that directory) but since the goal of the probes is only to test the files distributed by OSG, I modified the probe to provide message and continue if there are IO problems. Scot, the new version is in SVN - revision 14787

The probe change will run the probe but will not fix 1.
Kevin, I read the ticket but I'm not clear on which version of OSG you have installed and how you obtained the CA certificates.
RPMs do not have versioned certificate directories and I think the current certificate version (also in OSG 1.2) is > 1.20, so I do not understand why you have certificates-1.13.

A clarification: also with GlobusWS containercert files are supposed to be in /etc/grid-security. The certificates directory should have only CA certificates and CRLs, ideally form one of the supported distributions (OSG, IGTF, ...), at most some custom CA but not other files.
Kevin, why did you copy the conteinercert files in the certificates directory? Is it required for some software?

Then some requests:
1. which is the output of "osg-version" ?
2. could you attach to the ticket the output of "ls -l /etc/grid-security/certificates/" (the final / should make it print the content, not the link)
3. could you attach to the ticket the output of: -bash-3.2$ python -c "import os; print [os.path.normcase(f) for f in os.listdir('/etc/grid-security/certificates')]"
4. below you said that you reinstalled the certificates. What did you do exactly?
5. If you have the RPM version (you mentioned using yum) can you run also: rpm -qi -f /etc/grid-security/certificates
6. And: yum list osg-ca-certs

Thank you,
Marco
    May 16, 2012 03:50 PM UTC by Scot Kronenfeld 
    The way the probe works is that it checks all certificates (in this
case, *.pem files) in a given directory.  It shouldn't check the
container files, but if they are copied in, that would explain it.

Why are the container* files copied into the certificates dir?  What
are you using the container certificate for?  It used to be used for
Globus-WS but we don't support that anymore.

On 5/16/2012 10:11 AM, Open Science Grid FootPrints wrote:
> [Duplicate message snipped]
    May 16, 2012 02:11 PM UTC by Scot Kronenfeld 
    Hi Kevin,
I've added the developer of the probe into the ticket.  He will be
able to help faster than I can, but I'll continue investigating in the
meantime.

I think the problem is that the probe is detecting the wrong directory
for your certificate installation.  The way the cert directory is
discovered is sensitive to what version of OSG you are running.  A few
questions

1) Where are your certificates actually installed?  If you installed
via RPM, they should be in /etc/grid-security/certificates
2) Do you have any of OSG_LOCATION, VDT_LOCATION, or GLOBUS_LOCATION set

On 5/15/2012 11:29 AM, Open Science Grid FootPrints wrote:
> [Duplicate message snipped]
    May 15, 2012 03:29 PM UTC by Scot Kronenfeld 
    No, it should not be owned by rsv.  But you should change the mode to
0444 so that the rsv user can read the file and therefore it won't
fail that check.

Note that containerkey.pem ('key', not 'cert') should be mode 0400.

##  Condor needs to create a few lock files to synchronize access to
##  various log files.  Because of problems we've had with network
##  filesystems and file locking over the years, we HIGHLY recommend
##  that you put these lock files on a local partition on each
##  machine.  If you don't have your LOCAL_DIR on a local partition,
##  be sure to change this entry.  Whatever user (or group) condor is
##  running as needs to have write access to this directory.  If
##  you're not running as root, this is whatever user you started up
##  the condor_master as.  If you are running as root, and there's a
